---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<Layout title="FAQ — Singapore Salary Calculator 2026" description="Frequently asked questions about Singapore salary calculations, CPF contributions, income tax, and take-home pay.">
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h1>

    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-6 border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">What is CPF and who has to contribute?</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          The Central Provident Fund (CPF) is Singapore's mandatory social security savings scheme. Both Singapore Citizens and Permanent Residents (and their employers) must make monthly CPF contributions. Foreigners on Employment Passes, S Passes, or Work Permits are not required to contribute to CPF.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-6 border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">What are the CPF contribution rates for 2026?</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          For Singapore Citizens and PRs (3rd year onwards) aged 55 and below, the employee contributes 20% and the employer contributes 17% of ordinary wages, totalling 37%. Rates decrease gradually for older age groups: 30% total for ages 55-60, 21% for ages 60-65, 16% for ages 65-70, and 12.5% for those above 70.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-6 border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">What is the CPF Ordinary Wage ceiling?</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          The CPF Ordinary Wage (OW) ceiling is $6,800 per month for 2026. This means CPF contributions are computed on the lower of your actual monthly ordinary wages or $6,800. If you earn more than $6,800 per month, only the first $6,800 is subject to CPF.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-6 border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">How is the Additional Wage ceiling calculated?</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          The Additional Wage (AW) ceiling for CPF purposes is $102,000 minus the total ordinary wages subject to CPF for the year. For instance, if your monthly OW subject to CPF is $6,800, your annual OW is $81,600, leaving an AW ceiling of $20,400 for bonus CPF contributions.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-6 border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">How is income tax calculated in Singapore?</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          Singapore uses a progressive income tax system. Your chargeable income (gross income minus reliefs and deductions) is taxed in bands, starting at 0% for the first $20,000 and increasing in steps up to 24% for income above $1,000,000. The effective tax rate is always lower than your top marginal rate.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-6 border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">What tax reliefs are available?</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          Common tax reliefs include Earned Income Relief ($1,000 for under 55, $6,000 for 55-59, $8,000 for 60+), CPF contribution relief (your employee CPF contributions), and NSman Relief ($3,000). Additional reliefs such as Spouse Relief, Child Relief, Parent Relief, and SRS contributions can further reduce your tax liability.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-6 border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">How are PR contribution rates different?</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          Permanent Residents follow a graduated CPF contribution schedule. In their 1st year of PR status, employee and employer rates are 5% and 4% respectively. In the 2nd year, these increase to 15% and 9%. From the 3rd year onwards, PRs contribute at the same rates as Singapore Citizens.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-6 border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Do foreigners pay tax in Singapore?</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          Yes, foreigners working in Singapore are subject to income tax. Non-resident foreigners (present for fewer than 183 days) are generally taxed at a flat rate of 15% or the progressive resident rates, whichever produces a higher tax. Resident foreigners (183+ days) are taxed on the same progressive scale as citizens.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-6 border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">What are the three CPF accounts?</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          CPF contributions are allocated into three accounts: the Ordinary Account (OA) for housing, insurance, investment, and education; the Special Account (SA) for retirement; and the MediSave Account (MA) for healthcare expenses and medical insurance. The allocation ratios change with the member's age.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-6 border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Is this calculator accurate?</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          This calculator uses official CPF Board contribution rates and IRAS tax brackets for YA2026. It provides estimates for general planning purposes. Individual circumstances such as additional tax reliefs, SDL, or specific bonus structures may affect your actual figures. For precise calculations, consult the CPF Board or IRAS directly.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
